review_blob: This stuff is just plain awful.  Extra Gold makes it sound like it should be better.  Ha!  A little more color (if you call it that) than Coors Light.

Very very very very light beer.  Wont slow you down?  Most people (women, those without livers, small pets, etc.) could down a 30-pack and still legally drive a car (or operate heavy machinery if so inclined).
Its a shame that retired athletes are endorsing this stuff.
More beery than the other Lambics.  Hence, its good.  However, it doesnt stack up as well to the other lambics (of Lindemans).
A little too sweet... its like drinking ice cream topping.  Bright scary red too.  Still, very drinkable and wonderfully sweet-smooth.
My favorite of the Lindemans lambics.  Its not as fruity (its currant, duh!) and has a little bit of a pine aroma and taste (its currant, duh!).  Funny thing is: I dont like currants.
Very, very tasty.  Seems almost like its not beer though, and that scares me.  Great for a lady too!
A very solid porter; very drinkable.  Not a Old World-style porter by any means however.
A little lighter (in flavor) than the porter, but still nice.  Since its a blend of porter and Yuengling Premium, you dont have the hoppiness that comes with some other brands (or a real B&T;).
The Yuengling taste with a bit more hop... hence the ale designation.  Pretty light; very drinkable.
The Yuengling taste... yet somehow always bad.  Their weakest product.
Not as good as the Yuengling Porter despite what the rankings might say.  Not a great lager but it does have that pleasant Yuengling taste.
For a light beer, this stuff is excellent and has a good flavor (unlike watered down light beers).
